@echo off
cd /d "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor"
echo ==== DAILY REPORT %DATE% %TIME% ==== >> "logs\daily.log"
type nul > "logs\run-start.flag"
start "SOC-hunt-watchdog" /b powershell -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\hunt-watchdog.ps1"
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily IIS web-attack hunt for the last 24 hours. Use the iis-log-hunt skill if available; otherwise hunt directly with the Graylog MCP tools. SCOPE: run coverage across ALL FOUR environments (OP-GL, PROD-GL, DEV-GL, AZ-GL) using base filter filebeat_log_file_path:*inetpub* - do not restrict to OP-GL only; named OP-GL streams include IIS_PROD and IIS_UAT, plus other IIS/Rebex/Exolution web streams. IIS field schema (stay within these): Client_ip, URI_Stream, URI_Query, Status, UserAgent, Referer, Time_Taken, Client_Bytes, Server_Bytes, Port, Host, Method. Suppress internal Nessus/Tenable scans at query time via a NOT UserAgent filter matching Nessus*, the literal Nessus SOAP, and Tenable* - BUT before suppressing any scanner-looking finding, check URI_Query for .nasl plugin filenames (Nessus run with a spoofed UA) and keep the finding if present. Internal RFC-1918 source IPs are NOT automatically safe - treat them as possible threat actors. Look for SQLi, XSS, path traversal, webshell, RCE, LFI/RFI, scanners, credential stuffing, SSRF, beaconing, web exfil. Aggregate first; do not pull millions of rows. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report - write ONLY the markdown file below, ending with the findings-json block. Save a concise markdown report to reports\iis-latest.md with findings, severity, evidence (timestamp, source IP, URL, status) and MITRE IDs. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. If a surface does not apply to an environment (e.g. Azure on OP-GL), include the section header with `Not applicable` or `No findings`. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries in the findings-json, not just HIGH/MEDIUM. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (iis|rdp|azure|linux), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model opus --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily RDP and Windows post-login hunt for the last 24 hours across all four Graylogs (Winlogbeat/Security: AZ-GL Winlog-Beat, PROD-GL Winlog_beat, DEV-GL Winlogbeat, OP-GL Winlog_beat). Use the rdp-windows-correlation-hunt skill if available; otherwise hunt directly via MCP. STREAM IDs are pre-resolved in C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\streams.json (by environment, title to id) - read it once and use those IDs to scope your searches directly; do NOT call list_streams. Fall back to list_streams only for a stream missing from that file or if a listed ID returns zero rows. FIELD CONVENTION (critical - wrong names return zero silently): use underscored Winlogbeat fields winlogbeat_winlog_event_id, winlogbeat_event_data_* (e.g. winlogbeat_event_data_TargetUserName, winlogbeat_event_data_IpAddress, winlogbeat_event_data_WorkstationName), winlogbeat_winlog_channel - NOT dotted winlog.event_id. Key event IDs: 4624 logon, 4625 failed logon, 4672 special privileges, 4688 process create, 4698/4702 scheduled task, 7045/4697 service install, 4720 new account, 4728/4732/4756 group add, 4719 audit policy change, 1102 security log cleared, 4648 explicit creds, 4776 NTLM, 5140/5145 share access, 4769 Kerberos (RC4 type 0x17 = Kerberoast), 4778/4779 RDP reconnect. Decode 4625 SubStatus: 0xC000006A bad password, 0xC0000234 locked, 0xC0000064 unknown user, 0xC000006F outside hours, 0xC0000072 disabled. Thresholds: failed-login burst = more than 3x 4625 by one user; late-night = 22:00-06:00 local; rapid hopping = under 5 min between different workstations. Escalate immediately (do not wait for the report): 1102 log clear; 4720+4728 by the same user within 10 min; 4769 RC4; 4624 type 10 to a Domain Controller from a non-admin IP; 4778 from a different client than the preceding 4779; PowerShell v2 downgrade; over 100 unique 5145 file accesses in under 10 min. Look for RDP brute force, failed-login bursts, late-night logons, tscon hijack, rapid workstation hopping, lateral movement, new admins. Aggregate first. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report - write ONLY the markdown file below, ending with the findings-json block. Save a concise markdown report to reports\rdp-latest.md with evidence and MITRE IDs. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. If a surface does not apply to an environment (e.g. Azure on OP-GL), include the section header with `Not applicable` or `No findings`. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries in the findings-json, not just HIGH/MEDIUM. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (iis|rdp|azure|linux), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model opus --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
echo ===AZURE-OUTPUT-START=== >> "logs\daily.log"
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily Entra/Azure identity hunt for the last 24 hours. Use the azure skill if available; otherwise query the Azure Event Hub streams across environments via MCP. TENANT-TO-STREAM ROUTING (one stream per tenant): mycasepoint.com -> AZ-GL stream 65cf0501c0fccf5d65f5025f; casepoint.com -> PROD-GL stream 6979bcc8245e61e78824df15; casepoint.in -> DEV-GL stream 69fb008584d94819ed097db0; OP-GL has NO Azure stream - do NOT run ANY query against OP-GL for Azure (it would only waste tokens); simply emit the ## OP-GL section as Not applicable. FIELD NAMES are real misspellings emitted by the content pack - use them verbatim or queries return zero silently: azure_prob_app_disply_name (disply not display), azure_prob_condi_access_status (condi not condit), azure_prop_resource_disply_name; the parser emits both azure_prob_* and azure_prop_* prefixes so OR them together (e.g. azure_prop_user_principal_name OR azure_prob_user_principal_name). IGNORE these Casepoint Cato egress IPs (they are not attackers): 140.82.202.196, 199.27.40.187, 123.253.153.138. Token-replay tell: MFA satisfied by claim in token from a new IP. Note azure_prob_device_detail_is_compliant is broken (false for ~99.6% of sign-ins) - do not rely on it for device posture. Look for risky sign-ins, MFA failure/bypass, impossible travel, token replay, cross-tenant access, conditional-access anomalies, new admin/role changes. Suppress noise codes 70043, 70044, 50173, 50140. Aggregate first. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report - write ONLY the markdown file below, ending with the findings-json block. You MUST call the Write tool to SAVE the full report to reports\azure-latest.md (overwrite any existing file) BEFORE you finish - do NOT only print it to the screen; the task is NOT complete until that file exists on disk, and printing the report instead of writing it is a failure. Save the markdown report to reports\azure-latest.md with evidence and MITRE IDs. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. If a surface does not apply to an environment (e.g. Azure on OP-GL), include the section header with `Not applicable` or `No findings`. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries in the findings-json, not just HIGH/MEDIUM. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (iis|rdp|azure|linux), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model opus --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
powershell -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -Command "$log=Get-Content 'C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\logs\daily.log' -Raw; $i=$log.LastIndexOf('===AZURE-OUTPUT-START==='); $az=if($i -ge 0){$log.Substring($i)}else{''}; $f='C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\reports\azure-latest.md'; $flag=(Get-Item 'C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\logs\run-start.flag').LastWriteTime; if((-not (Test-Path $f)) -or ((Get-Item $f).LastWriteTime -lt $flag)){ if($az -match 'findings-json'){ [IO.File]::WriteAllText($f,$az); Write-Output 'AZURE FALLBACK: rebuilt azure-latest.md from captured log output' } else { Write-Output 'AZURE FALLBACK FAILED: no findings-json in azure output - manual check needed' } } else { Write-Output 'Azure wrote azure-latest.md normally' }" >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily Linux hunt for the last 24 hours across all four Graylogs (Rsyslog/syslog/auth/secure/audit streams). Use the sd-linux skill if available; otherwise hunt directly via MCP. STREAM IDs are pre-resolved in C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\streams.json (by environment, title to id) - read it once and use those IDs to scope your searches directly; do NOT call list_streams. Fall back to list_streams only for a stream missing from that file or if a listed ID returns zero rows. Look for sshd brute force, sudo abuse, reverse shells, cryptominers (xmrig, kdevtmpfsi, kinsing, sysrv), cron/systemd/authorized_keys persistence, /etc/passwd|shadow|sudoers tampering. Useful fields: source, message, application_name/program, facility, level, pid, and auditd fields auditd_type, auditd_exe, auditd_comm, auditd_uid, auditd_auid when present; fall back to message substring matching if a field is absent. Treat strings jndi and ceurufrd as allow-listed known, with ONE override: if a jndi line is paired with an active kill-chain signal on the same host within 60s (outbound LDAP/RMI, curl/wget to /tmp, reverse-shell pattern, new uid=0, or /etc/passwd write), override the allow-list and promote to HIGH. Correlation pass: two REVIEW signals on the same host+user or host+src_ip within 1 hour upgrade to HIGH. Aggregate first. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report - write ONLY the markdown file below, ending with the findings-json block. Save a concise markdown report to reports\linux-latest.md with evidence and MITRE IDs. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. If a surface does not apply to an environment (e.g. Azure on OP-GL), include the section header with `Not applicable` or `No findings`. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries in the findings-json, not just HIGH/MEDIUM. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (iis|rdp|azure|linux), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model opus --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily SFTP and DTC hunt for the last 24 hours. Use the sftp-graylog-hunt skill's detection logic if available; otherwise hunt directly via MCP. STREAM IDs are pre-resolved in C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\streams.json (by environment, title to id) - read it once and use those IDs to scope your searches directly; do NOT call list_streams. Fall back to list_streams only for a stream missing from that file or if a listed ID returns zero rows. SFTP streams are named differently per Graylog - use the right names: PROD-GL = External_SFTP_cerebus + Internal_SFTP_cerebus; OP-GL = External_SFTP + Internal_SFTP; DEV-GL = single combined stream SFTP_cerebus; AZ-GL has NO SFTP streams - do NOT run ANY query against AZ-GL for SFTP (it would only waste tokens); simply emit the ## AZ-GL section as Not applicable. DTC = Rebex streams Rebex_PROD, Rebex_CA, Rebex_PT. ALLOWLIST - these three are Casepoint Cato egress IPs, NOT external attackers: 140.82.202.196, 199.27.40.187, 123.253.153.138. When any appears as the client/source IP, cap severity at MEDIUM and tag the finding 'Cato egress - likely false positive'; do not silently drop it if a real attack pattern is present (webshell path, executable upload, credential filename), but never treat a Cato IP as a confirmed external threat. Cerberus SFTP message decoding: 'Successfully stored file at' = upload (client to server), 'Successfully sent file' = download (server to client), 'Key exchange failed' or 'SSL accept error' or 'wrong version number' = SSH/TLS scanner probe; the username appears after the IP in brackets and session id ties events together. Useful fields: Client_ip (remote IP), Origin_ip (ASN/geo string), Size_In_MB (0 means non-transfer event). Look for SFTP brute force, failed-login spikes, large transfers / exfil, suspicious file extensions, malware or executable drops, anomalous file-share behavior. For auth failures, distinguish BURST (many failures within 60s from one IP = brute force, higher severity) from SCATTERED (spread over hours = low-and-slow or noise, lower severity); require a correlated second indicator before calling anything HIGH. Aggregate first; do not pull millions of rows. Do NOT generate the skill's own PDF - instead save a concise markdown report to reports\sftp-latest.md with findings, severity, evidence (timestamp, source IP, file, bytes) and MITRE IDs. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. If a surface does not apply to an environment, include the section header with `Not applicable` or `No findings`. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries in the findings-json, not just HIGH/MEDIUM. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (sftp|dtc), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model opus --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a daily INFRASTRUCTURE and SECURITY-APPLIANCE hunt for the last 24 hours across all four Graylogs, covering the log sources NOT handled by the other hunts. There is no skill for these - hunt directly via MCP. STEP 1: Read the local file C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\infra-streams.json - it is the PRE-RESOLVED stream-ID map for all 8 categories across the 4 GLs. Use the stream IDs from that file DIRECTLY and do NOT call list_streams (that discovery is the main token waste this map removes). For each category query ONLY the stream IDs listed under that GL; if a GL is not listed for a category, that category is Not Applicable there - do not probe for it. The categories: FIREWALL (Fortigate; VPN rides Fortigate), EDR-AV (ESET), MFA (Securenvoy), EXFIL MONITOR (Outgoing Traffic Monitor - DEV-GL only, event-driven, empty is normal, report only on a breach alert), DATA SERVICES (Postgres pgbouncer, Redis, RabbitMQ, plus search via Elasticsearch), SWITCHES, LOAD BALANCER (KEMP), VIRTUALIZATION and OUT-OF-BAND MGMT (vCenter/ESXi/iLO/UCS). The map already excludes known-dead streams. FALLBACK: only if a listed stream ID returns zero rows across the whole window may you call list_streams for that single category+GL to re-resolve by title, and note that the cached ID looks stale. STEP 2: aggregate first per category (counts and top-N), then drill down only on anomalies (cap 10 rows). TOKEN + LATENCY BUDGET (strict - these streams are huge AND slow to scan server-side, so queries must be FEW and INDEX-SELECTIVE): every query MUST be a single aggregate_logs call (counts / top-N) with an explicit small limit - NEVER pull raw rows, NEVER aggregate over * , and NEVER use a broad free-text match that forces a full scan. HARD CAP: at most ONE aggregate_logs call per category per GL (not two), plus at most ONE small drill-down (<=10 rows) per CONFIRMED HIGH only. Use a narrow, index-friendly filter per category: FIREWALL (Fortigate) -> action:deny only (do not OR-in extra terms); EDR (ESET) -> threat/detection/quarantine/infiltration events only; MFA (Securenvoy) -> failure/denied/lockout only; DATA SERVICES (keep the high-volume ones especially tight) -> RabbitMQ = auth-failure / access-refused only, Redis = the dangerous commands CONFIG|SLAVEOF|FLUSHALL|MODULE or auth errors only, Postgres/pgbouncer = FATAL auth or role errors only, Elasticsearch = error OR FATAL only; SWITCHES -> link-change OR auth-failure OR config-change; VIRT and LOAD BALANCER -> login OR permission-change OR VM-lifecycle OR config-change. The high-volume streams (Fortigate, RabbitMQ, Redis, Elasticsearch) are the slow ones - keep their filter to a single narrow indexed clause, and if a category's one aggregate does not return promptly, do NOT mark it clean - emit a REVIEW finding for that category (sev REVIEW, finding 'NOT ASSESSED this run - <category> aggregate did not return in time = coverage gap', action 're-run this category manually') and MOVE ON rather than retrying or broadening. NEVER record a slow or skipped category as 'No findings' - a gap must be visible, not hidden. This keeps result sets small and queries fast WITHOUT ever silently dropping coverage. WHAT TO HUNT: FIREWALL - denied/blocked spikes from one external IP, port-scan fan-out (one src to many dst ports), IPS/IDS signature hits, geo-anomalous allows, VPN or admin auth failures, firewall config changes, any inbound allow to mgmt ports 22/3389/445 from external IPs. EDR-ESET - ANY malware or threat detection, quarantine, real-time-protection-disabled, or threat-not-cleaned event is at least a HIGH candidate; report host, threat name, action, and whether it was cleaned. MFA-Securenvoy - auth failures, repeated denials, lockouts, token or seed errors, admin changes. EXFIL MONITOR - any threshold-breach or over-quota alert is an exfil candidate; name the host and volume. DATA SERVICES - auth failures, connection floods, Redis unauthenticated commands (CONFIG/SLAVEOF/MODULE/FLUSHALL), Postgres FATAL auth or role errors, error spikes suggesting injection or scanning, config changes. VIRTUALIZATION-OOB - interactive or failed admin/root logins to vCenter/ESXi/iLO/UCS from unexpected IPs, VM create/delete/clone/export, datastore browse or download, account or permission changes, SSH enabled on ESXi. SWITCHES - link up/down flapping, running-config changes, repeated auth failures to switch management, port-security violations, unexpected SNMP or admin access. LOAD BALANCER (KEMP) - admin logins and failures, virtual-service or rule changes, certificate changes, TLS handshake error spikes, health-check state flapping. ALLOW-LIST: the three Casepoint Cato egress IPs 140.82.202.196, 199.27.40.187, 123.253.153.138 are shared corporate egress - cap their severity at MEDIUM and tag 'Cato egress - likely false positive', but do not drop a real attack pattern. Internal RFC-1918 IPs are NOT automatically safe. Aggregate first. You MUST use the Write tool to SAVE the report to reports\infra-latest.md (overwrite any existing file) BEFORE finishing - the task is NOT complete until that file exists on disk; printing it instead of writing it is a failure. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report. Structure the markdown with exactly 4 sections, one per environment, each starting on its own line: ## AZ-GL, ## PROD-GL, ## DEV-GL, ## OP-GL. Under each, note each category checked with No findings or Not applicable where nothing fired. Do not add other top-level ## headers. After the per-env sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array of finding objects, then closing three backticks. One object per distinct finding (include a CLEAN entry per env if nothing fired). Never silently drop a finding; include LOW and REVIEW entries too. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (AZ-GL|PROD-GL|DEV-GL|OP-GL), surface (one of firewall|edr|mfa|exfil|db|virt|switch|lb), finding (<=120 chars), evidence (<=100 chars - timestamps, IPs, counts), mitre (T-code list or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model sonnet --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
powershell -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\prep-correlation.ps1" >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
powershell -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\correlation-gate.ps1" >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
