call "C:\Users\VidhyaV\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd" -p "Run a CROSS-MODULE correlation and kill-chain reconstruction pass for today's daily hunt. Do NOT re-hunt raw logs broadly. INPUT: read the single file reports\_merged-findings.json - a compact JSON array of EVERY finding from all 6 hunts (each object has sev, env, surface, finding, evidence, mitre, action). This merged file is your ONLY input; do NOT read the per-hunt markdown files (saves tokens). Build an entity index across ALL findings: source/client IPs, usernames/accounts, hostnames/workstations, and timestamps. GOAL: find attack chains that span more than one surface or more than one environment - the thing single-surface hunts cannot see. CORRELATE when two or more findings from DIFFERENT surfaces (iis/rdp/azure/linux/sftp/firewall/edr/mfa/exfil/db/virt/switch/lb) or different envs share an entity (same IP, same username, same host) OR cluster in a tight time window on the same host/env. For each correlation, reconstruct the kill chain and map each step in order to a MITRE ATT&CK tactic (Reconnaissance, Initial Access, Execution, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, Defense Evasion, Credential Access, Discovery, Lateral Movement, Collection, Command and Control, Exfiltration, Impact). ALLOW-LIST: the three Casepoint Cato egress IPs 140.82.202.196, 199.27.40.187, 123.253.153.138 are shared corporate egress, NOT attacker pivots - never anchor a kill chain on them. CONFIRMATION (optional, bounded): you MAY run at most 5 targeted aggregation queries via the Graylog MCP to confirm a HIGH-confidence suspected link (e.g. whether one source IP appears across two surfaces on the same host in the window) - aggregate only, never pull raw rows, never exceed 5 queries total. SEVERITY: a confirmed multi-stage chain spanning surfaces = HIGH; a plausible but unconfirmed shared-entity link = REVIEW; a weak or coincidental overlap = LOW. If NO cross-surface or cross-env chain exists, say so explicitly. You MUST use the Write tool to SAVE the report to reports\correlation-latest.md (overwrite any existing file) BEFORE finishing - the task is NOT complete until that file exists on disk; printing it instead of writing it is a failure. Do NOT generate your own PDF or skill-native report. Structure the markdown with these sections: '## Kill Chains' (one subsection per reconstructed chain with the ordered MITRE stages, the shared entity, the contributing findings by surface and env, and a confidence level), '## Correlated Entities' (the IPs/users/hosts that appeared in more than one finding), and '## Cross-Check Coverage' (which entities were cross-checked and what was ruled out). After those sections, on a new line, append a fenced code block: three backticks followed by findings-json (so it reads as ```findings-json), then a valid JSON array, then closing three backticks. One object per reconstructed chain (include one CLEAN object if no cross-surface chain was found). Never silently drop a correlation; include LOW and REVIEW entries too. Keys: sev (HIGH|MEDIUM|REVIEW|LOW|CLEAN), env (the environment(s) involved, e.g. OP-GL or OP-GL+DEV-GL), surface (always the literal correlation), finding (<=120 chars - the chain summary), evidence (<=100 chars - shared entity plus contributing surfaces plus timestamps), mitre (T-code list across the chain or empty), action (<=100 chars concrete next step), query (the exact Graylog/Elasticsearch query string you actually ran to surface this finding), investigate (a concrete Graylog query the analyst should run NEXT for deeper investigation - pivot on the IP, user, or host and name the stream/fields). Plain ASCII only inside JSON strings; no smart quotes, em-dashes, or emoji." --model sonnet --permission-mode bypassPermissions --mcp-config "C:\Users\VidhyaV\soc-monitor\.mcp.json" --strict-mcp-config --max-turns 200 < NUL >> "logs\daily.log" 2>&1
